    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="roman" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Latn">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name>QVENVENDAN<hi rend="inverted">I</hi></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><w><hi rend="ligature">FI</hi><hi rend="ligature">LI</hi></w><name>BARCVN<hi rend="inverted">I</hi></name></persName>            
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>'of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Quenvendanus</foreign> son of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Barcunus</foreign>'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><q>The inscription uses the 'X son of Y' formula in the genitive case. There is no corresponding ogam inscription... Both names are Irish and relatively late (post-syncope). QVENVENDANI (genitive) is a later form of the name seen in Ireland in ogam on (Macalister 1945, 3-4 CIIC: no 2) QENOVENDAGNI... the ancestor of Irish <hi rend="italic">Cennf(h)innán</hi>, 'white-headed one'... BARCVNI is a Latinized genitive of the ancestor of the Old Irish name <hi rend="italic">Barrchú</hi>, 'dog-head' (although theoretically it could be a British name <hi rend="italic">*Bargwn).</hi></q> (Edwards 2007, 219).</p>
                <p>Macalister (1922) suggested Ogham: --]NVENDANIM[--]B[-]R[--Latin: QVENVENDANI; FILIBARCVUNI</p>
            </div>
